<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 93 / Top Spanish bank faces break-up as board is dismissed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of Spain yesterday dismissed the board of Banco Espanol de Credito,
the country's fourth-largest bank, raising the possibility that Banesto
might be broken up and its industrial empire shared among the rest of
Spain's big banks.
The central bank acted after market rumours of Banesto's imminent failure
sent its stock into free fall yesterday morning and started a run on
deposits in Madrid.
Trading in the stock was suspended at midday, with the price having fallen
about 7 per cent to Pta2,135 (Pounds 10.46).
Mr Alfredo Saenz, deputy chairman of Banco Bilbao Vizcaya, was named by the
Bank of Spain as Banesto's new chairman in place of Mr Mario Conde, the
former industrialist who took charge of Banesto in 1987. Mr Conde has tried
to persuade the authorities that Banesto, the most vulnerable of Spain's
large banks, could survive on its own.
Mr Saenz and four other directors - one each from Banco Central Hispano,
Banco Santander, Argentaria, the state-owned banking group, and Banco
Popular - took charge of Banesto late yesterday afternoon.
The threatened failure of Banesto and the removal of Mr Conde will be a
bitter blow to JP Morgan, the US investment bank, and its deputy chairman,
Mr Roberto Mendoza, who was recently named to the now dismissed Banesto
board. Banesto was the first investment of the Dollars 1bn Corsair banking
fund created by JP Morgan. Corsair owns nearly 9 per cent of Banesto. JP
Morgan also acted as an adviser this year to Banesto during the raising of
nearly Dollars 700m in new capital. Yesterday, the US bank said Corsair
planned to maintain its position.
Mr Alfredo Pastor, the deputy economy minister, said a Bank of Spain
inspection at Banesto had found a much larger equity deficit than
anticipated.
The results of this inspection had been studied by Mr Luis Angel Rojo,
governor of the Bank of Spain, and senior staff just two weeks ago. Urgent
talks had taken place with Banesto about ways to shore up its finances.
Mr Pastor said no decision had been made about Banesto's future. 'The
intervention today is the end of a long process,' he said. An inspection in
1992 had detected gaps in Banesto's finances but the central bank and Mr
Conde had agreed upon a timetable to raise new equity and to rebalance the
bank's loan portfolio. But, Mr Pastor said, 'the situation in 1993 has
worsened' even though Banesto raised more than Dollars 1bn in capital
through share sales and disposals.
A central bank statement said: 'Banesto's current situation obliges it to
take restructuring measures that cannot be undertaken alone and which
require the support of the whole banking system.' It said it had acted in
order to guarantee the liquidity of Banesto.
It had been assumed that the money raised with JP Morgan's help this year,
plus the proceeds of the sale of a banking subsidiary to Deutsche Bank, had
raised Banesto's equity levels above ratios demanded by Spanish and European
authorities.
The Banesto group reported losses of Pta5.7bn (Pounds 27.9m) for the first
nine months of 1993.
Banesto: walking on a razor's edge, Page 15
</TEXT>
