<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 93 / Television and Radio Review: Music to suit all tastes -
Christmas Eve
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Above all today there is music: for traditionalists and those who still
truly enjoy Christmas, Radio 4 provides its live relay, as ever, of The
Festival Of Nine Lessons And Carols from King's College, Cambridge on Radio
4 at 3pm. (Incidentally, for those who regularly inquire 'Why can't you buy
a radio recorder to tape programmes while you are out?' the answer is that
you can: Argos sell a good cheap version, and there are more expensive sets
elsewhere.) There is an entirely different 60-minute television programme
offering Carols From King's on BBC2 at 6pm with 13 Christmas songs and just
four readings.
For lovers of the rock/soul/Tamla sound, Channel 4 offers an hour each of
Tina Turner and Diana Ross: Tina Turner, What's Love Live (9pm) recorded in
California during her US tour this summer; and Diana Ross, The Lady Sings
recorded in a nightclub setting in New York (11.05pm). Given the way the
divas are now being marketed, it will be interesting to see how the ratings
for Turner and Ross compare with BBC2's The Sorceress, with Kiri Te Kanawa,
(9.30pm). The popular New Zealander sings seven Handel arias.
The South Bank Show offers an excessive 90 minutes on Cliff Richard, saying
that 'for the first time he has allowed a documentary crew into his life
with unlimited access' (10.20pm, ITV); and for middle-aged ravers still
proud of their virtuosity in the last dance craze that was actually taught,
C4 provides the same astonishing amount of time for Twist (7pm).
</TEXT>
