<DATE>931224
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 93 / Television and Radio Review: Porgy and Bess bring mixed
emotions - Music
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Opera features more prominently than usual in the 1993 end-of-year
television timetable. A wider range of it than usual, too: from the
elaborate confection of dance and song entitled The Sorceress (BBC2,
Christmas Eve), with music taken from Handel's opera Alcina and Kiri Te
Kanawa personifying the eponymous mistress of magic arts, to Gershwin's
Porgy and Bess (BBC2, Christmas Sunday) represents an interesting and,
indeed, artistically ambitious span of operatic material.
The Porgy, directed by Trevor Nunn and based on his celebrated 1986
Glyndebourne Festival production, should have been one of the highlights of
the festive-season viewing schedule. For the vast majority of viewers, who
will not have seen the show either at Glyndebourne or in its recent brief
transfer to the Royal Opera House, Covent Garden, it may well be just that.
At least almost all of the unforgettable original principals - Willard White
and Cynthia Haymon in the title roles, Damon Evans (Sporting Life), Gregg
Baker (Crown) and Marietta Simpson (Maria) - were retained; as a record of
their marvellous, heart-wrenching performances the film retains a basic
value.
But alas, some badly misguided decision-making went into the planning of the
film, the results of which (on the evidence of an advance video sampling)
betray themselves in just about every frame.
Most misguided idea of all was to re-mount the production - on, it seems, a
rather slender budget and an exiguous notion of set-design - in a studio and
then have the vocal contributions mimed: what we hear on the soundtrack is
actually the equally celebrated 1989 EMI studio recording of the
Glyndebourne Porgy, conducted by Simon Rattle.
The deadening effect of the dubbing, of singer-actors not directly involved
in the singing part of the job but simply mouthing their words, is
undeniable and, indeed, unavoidable. Anyone who recalls the spellbinding
immediacy of the Glyndebourne experience would be well advised to rely on
memories and skip the whole relay.
By contrast, the films of Puccini's Fanciulla del West (C4, Christmas Day),
Tchaikovsky's Queen of Spades (BBC2, Monday) and Strauss's 'conversation
piece' Capriccio (BBC2, Tuesday) are taken from live productions. While this
may seem a cop-out in terms of confronting the two media - the
musico-theatrical and the televisual - it has in these three cases ensured
that the three shows are put across with their basic qualities intact.
The Puccini, with Domingo and Barbara Daniels, comes from the New York Met;
the Tchaikovsky is another recent Glyndebourne enterprise, a magnificently
creepy modern re-thinking of the terrifying masterpiece; and the Strauss,
again with Kiri Te Kanawa, is a John Cox staging from the San Francisco
Opera.
Also worth noting for the new year weekend: La Traviata, filmed at the
Fenice, Venice, the theatre where Verdi's opera was premiered (BBC2, New
Year's Eve); and a re-run of the remarkable, endlessly fascinating
conversations that in 1968 the BBC filmed between Maria Callas and her old
friend and longtime admirer Lord Harewood (BBC2, New Year's Eve and New
Year's Day).
</TEXT>
<XX>
