<DATE>931224
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 93 / International Company News: Fiat reduces construction
exposure in three-way link
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Fiat, Italy's biggest private company, is cutting its exposure to the
troubled building sector via a complex three-way merger. The deal will
create the country's biggest construction concern.
Fiat will merge its quoted Cogefar-Impresit subsidiary with Lodigiani and
Girola, two large, privately-owned, building groups. The combined entity,
with annual sales of about L2,800bn (Dollars 1.7bn), should be more
competitive against larger rivals, such as Germany's Hochtief and Philipp
Holzmann and Bouygues of France, for big international contracts.
The multi-stage deal will begin with a rights issue by Cogefar-Impresit, 63
per cent-owned by Fiat, which will then merge with Impregilo. The latter is
a long-standing joint venture between Cogefar-Impresit, Lodigiani and
Girola, operating exclusively in big infrastructure contracts outside Italy.
The merged company, to be called Impregilo, will then take over the
industrial activities of Lodigiani and Girola in return for equity stakes.
Fiat's stake in the 'new' Impregilo will fall to about 26.5 per cent when
the deal is completed during the next 18 months. A similar proportion of the
shares will be floating. The remainder will be split between Lodigiani (17
per cent), Girola (16.3 per cent), and five banks (15 per cent).
'The deal reflects an awareness that the companies concerned need to
concentrate and rationalise,' said Mr Ugo Montevecchi, chief executive of
Cogefar-Impresit. 'The existing Impregilo joint venture was the obvious
point on which to focus.'
Italy's big builders have been devasted this year by recession and the
long-running political corruption scandal, which has led to a virtual freeze
on public-sector contracts. Profits have crumbled at most large groups,
while many smaller builders, which often act as subcontractors, have gone
bankrupt.
Mr Montevecchi said the Fiat-led reorganisation was dictated by market
forces in the highly-fragmented Italian construction sector.
Cogefar-Impresit, the country's leading builder, expects sales of about
L1,600bn this year, while turnover at Lodigiani and Girola should be about
L500bn and L300bn respectively.
</TEXT>
