<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 93 / Order, order, as MPs stock up: The Palace of Westminster's
retail success story
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Deep in the Palace of Westminster - between Strangers' Bar and the staircase
to the members' tearoom - business is brisk in the most successful small
retail outlet in the country.
Chancellor Kenneth Clarke, in sports jacket and corduroys, peruses the list
of chocolates, alcoholic beverages and accessories, all bearing the
distinctive House of Commons portcullis, before making his selection.
Mr Tony Banks, never at a loss for a quip, has just told Mr Clarke that if
the whole economy was doing as well as this little shop, Britain would be a
happier place.
After purchasing his bulk order, the Labour MP for Newham North West
explains that each year he dons his Father Christmas hat and gives mints and
wine to those who have helped in his constituency advice surgery. Goods from
the shop - which range from gunpowder mustard to jacquard-lined dress
wallets - are also 'useful for raffle prizes at constituencies', he says.
A few minutes later a denim-jacketed Mr Calum MacDonald prepares to lug a
cardboard box full of sherry and mints towards the members' staircase. As
Labour MP for the remote Western Isles, Mr MacDonald faces the problem of
trying to 'clamber aboard the shuttle' with his acquisitions.
He, more than most, appreciates the MPs' privilege of being able to have
their whisky orders sent direct to their constituencies. The shop's
merchandise, he says, makes popular presents in hospitals and old people's
homes.
Measured by sales per sq ft, this tiny souvenir kiosk outstrips all British
rivals. And as with the retail trade in general, the approach to Christmas
is by far its busiest period. On the heaviest days, Mr Jose Alba, Mr Fidel
Benserghine and its other green-jacketed stewards say they can shift as many
as 2,500 to 3,000 boxes of mints and up to 25 boxes of whisky.
According to Mrs Sue Harrison, director of catering services at the Commons,
December accounts for nearly a third of the annual sales of Pounds 670,000.
This turnover is doubly impressive as, according to a recent catering
committee report, there has been 'a restriction on the amount of stock which
can be available in the kiosk'. It ran out of chocolates for two days this
month.
A notice to customers says: 'Unfortunately, the after-dinner mints, coffee
creams and orange creams will not reappear before Christmas due to a
manufacturers' packaging deficiency.'
Sales are also, at present, generated predominantly from the 651 MPs and
3,000 or so others who work in the palace.
But proposals are afoot to change this. Subject to various approvals, a new
kiosk - more easily accessible to the 800 tourists a day who visit the
Commons - may soon be erected in Westminster Hall. The new facility could be
operating after next year's summer recess and in time for next Christmas.
There are even plans for a visitor centre, but these are not expected to
come to fruition until early next century.
</TEXT>
<XX>
