<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A housing-market recovery next year, in spite of factors such as reduced
real incomes because of tax increases, is forecast today by the Council of
Mortgage Lenders, Alison Smith writes.
The council, which represents building societies and centralised lenders
such as banks, says the stabilising of house prices and the likelihood of a
small rise next year, with the reduction in negative equity and better
employment prospects, will boost confidence.
It believes these will outweigh elements such as the fall in mortgage
interest tax relief and the greater expense of becoming an owner-occupier.
