<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 93 / Government firm on Andersen ban
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday rejected efforts by accountants Arthur Andersen to
have a ban on the firm doing public-sector work lifted.
The Treasury solicitor wrote yesterday to Herbert Smith, Andersen's lawyers,
rejecting the firm's claim that the action could be in breach of European
law.
Andersen has not obtained public-sector work for nearly a decade since it
was sued by the government for alleged negligence as auditor to De Lorean,
the car company.
The Treasury said that its ban on Andersen obtaining auditing, privatisation
advisory and other accounting work would remain while litigation was in
progress.
It emerged this week that the firm had approached the government in the
autumn after enactment of new European Union legislation suggesting that
outstanding litigation need not be a barrier to tenders for other work.
Earlier this year the government recommended a ban on giving any work to 13
named partners and staff at accountants Touche Ross. However Touche as a
firm continues to receive work.
</TEXT>
