<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 93 / Tecs seek approval for mergers with chambers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Training and enterprise councils are to advise the government not to object
to their integration with chambers of commerce, provided that a number of
quality criteria are met.
If ministers accept this advice, which comes after the government invited
Tecs' comments, a number of mergers could take place.
The move would be unpopular in some areas but would be in line with wider
moves to redraw the map of locally delivered business and economic
development services. Kent Tec, for example, is negotiating with Kent County
Council over its integration with the county's economic development unit.
The quality criteria could include obliging the new bodies not to be
deliverers of services. At present many chambers give contracts to Tecs to
provide training.
Chambers, which are private bodies, and Tecs are already co-operating in the
new Business Links outlets which deliver services to small businesses. But a
number would like to go further.
In the past the Department of Employment has set demanding criteria before
considering mergers, saying that the two organisations have different aims
and remits. Chambers, it has said, exist to serve the needs of their
business membership while Tecs were set up by the government to provide
support for training and economic development.
