<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 93 / London outpaces continental bourses as investors pour in
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN and WILLIAM COCHRANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The London stock market climbed to another record close yesterday as dealers
scrambled for shares to balance their trading books before Christmas.
The move reflected a positive investment environment throughout continental
Europe where five of the six top bourses hit new highs yesterday.
German institutional investors took Frankfurt up just more than 1 per cent
to a fresh record as west German inflation figures showed a slowing monthly
figure. Paris was lifted to its highest close by a strong French bond market
and an inflow from mutual funds.
Among the others, in Zurich, Amsterdam and Madrid, equities hit their fifth
consecutive record figures, boosted by continued strong liquidity and hopes
of lower interest rates in the new year.
But the gain of about 1.2 per cent in London outpaced gains in the other
European bourses.
The FT-SE 100 Index, which represents the UK's 100 most highly valued
companies, closed up 40.8 on the day at 3,396.5 after breaking briefly
through 3,400.
The London market is fuelled by hopes that bank base rates will fall again
in the new year, down from the current 5.5 per cent. Renewed demand for
shares yesterday caught out the market-making firms, which were already
having great difficulty finding stock for delivery to the buyers who have
been driving the market ahead for the past month.
The FT-SE 100 has risen more than 1,000 points since the UK left the
European exchange rate mechanism in September 1992. This year investment
institutions and the securities firms that service them have made
substantial profits.
Buying pressure was exacerbated by continuing background activity in the
derivatives markets. Foreign investors have been funnelling money into the
UK since the summer and using derivatives as an efficient way into the stock
market.
Paris bourse record, Page 2
London stocks, Page 13
World stocks, Page 19
Markets, Weekend, Page XI
