<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 93 / International Company News: US defence contractors agree
deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Martin Marietta is to buy the space systems business of fellow defence
contractor General Dynamics for Dollars 208.5m in cash, the two US companies
announced yesterday.
The deal, which had been rumoured in the industry for several months, allows
Martin Marietta to enter the market for intermediate-sized rockets. It
already produces the Titan rocket, which is used to launch heavy satellites.
General Dynamics makes the smaller Atlas-Centaur launch system.
The sale underscores the sharply differing strategies of the two companies
to cope with shrinking defence spending following the collapse of the Soviet
empire.
General Dynamics has shrunk by selling off large parts of its defence
business, while Martin Marietta has been an aggressive buyer.
Its acquisitions include General Electric's aerospace unit for Dollars 3bn
last year.
General Dynamics will retain ownership of the space division's real estate,
including a 40-acre tract in San Diego with a Dollars 50m book value.
The space division had 1992 sales of Dollars 500m, employs 3,700 and has a
backlog of around Dollars 2.5bn.
</TEXT>
