FT  23 DEC 93 / International Company News: Flight operations hold back
Swissair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Swissair will make a small consolidated profit again this year, in spite of
suffering a large loss on its flight operations for the fourth consecutive
year.
The company's forecast was slightly more optimistic than that made in the
summer when the Swiss national airline said it would be difficult to break
even this year.
Mr Otto Loepfe, chief executive, said in a newsletter to staff that results
in September and October were 'pleasing,' with the load factor reaching 70.6
per cent in October.
Nevertheless, prices remained depressed and a 'massive loss' would again be
recorded on airline operations. Only substantial proceeds from aircraft
sales and profits from subsidiaries would make possible the overall group
profit.
Last year, the group made a SFr113m (Dollars 75.80m) net profit, due to
SFr179m from aircraft sales.
Following the collapse last month of the Alcazar negotiations aimed at
merging Swissair and three other medium sized European airlines, Mr Loepfe
said the group approved SFr211m in new capital spending on buildings and
installations.
He said the airline would concentrate on strengthening its existing
alliances with Delta Air Lines of the US, Singapore Airlines, Austrian
Airlines and Scandinavian Airlines System.
</TEXT>
