<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 93 / Ferranti managers may make bid to receivers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A seven-man team of senior Ferranti International managers is preparing a
bid for the bulk of the defence electronics company, which is in
receivership.
The team, led by Mr Phil Burton, Ferranti's director of marketing, is aiming
to put together a consortium in the new year and begin detailed financial
negotiations in February.
'It has become clear to us that, shorn of problems stemming from the ISC
acquisition, the group has a bright future,' Mr Burton said yesterday.
The initial proposals envisage the management group teaming up with UK or
overseas partners to mount a bid for most of Ferranti's non-manufacturing
operations.
It is understood that Ferranti's components business, which manufactures
specialist hardware and sub-systems, would not be included in the bid.
Ferranti's highly successful simulation and training business has attracted
interest from potential purchasers and may be sold separately.
The management consortium proposals were immediately welcomed by Mr Murdoch
McKillop and Mr John Talbot, the two administrative receivers from Arthur
Andersen, appointed to the ailing group after GEC withdrew a 1p-a-share
rescue bid in December. They said there were a number of long-term options
for the businesses.
The receivers added they had been approached by a large number of UK and
overseas groups that had expressed an interest in acquiring Ferranti
businesses.
Mr Burton said a re-born Ferranti would have to be well capitalised and
strong enough to compete in the international defence and civil markets. He
said these factors put it beyond the reach of an ordinary management
buy-out. Therefore, he said, the management team, which is being advised by
Mr Richard Stone of Coopers and Lybrand Corporate Finance, was proposing a
consortium bid, 'backed by long-term players in these nationally important
sectors'.
He said initial discussions with the receivers and potential partners from
the UK and overseas had been 'very encouraging'. While emphasising that it
remained early days, he said 'we do plan to be in a position to commence
formal purchase negotiations in February'.
</TEXT>
